  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How long can I stay outside the UK as a dependant of the tier2 visa?",
  "response": "As a dependent of a Tier 2 (General) visa holder in the UK, there are specific rules regarding how long you can stay outside the UK without affecting your visa status. Here's what you need to know:\n\n### **Key Rules:**\n1. **Continuous Residency Requirement:** You must not spend more than **180 days outside the UK in any 12-month period** if you plan to apply for Indefinite Leave to Remain (ILR) in the future. Staying outside the UK for longer than this could break your continuous residency, which is a requirement for ILR.\n\n2. **Visa Validity:** Your dependent visa remains valid as long as the main Tier 2 visa holder's visa is valid, provided you meet the conditions of your visa, including not exceeding the allowed time outside the UK.\n\n3. **Maintaining Dependence:** You must continue to depend on the main Tier 2 visa holder. If you leave the UK for an extended period and are no longer living with the main visa holder, it could affect your dependent status.\n\n4. **Travel Records:** Keep track of your travel dates and ensure you do not exceed the 180-day limit in any 12-month period if you plan to apply for ILR.\n\n### **What Happens If You Exceed the Limit?**\n- If you stay outside the UK for more than 180 days in a 12-month period, it may break your continuous residency, making you ineligible for ILR.\n- If you exceed the allowed absence without a valid reason, it could also lead to the cancellation of your dependent visa.\n\n### **Exceptions:**\nThere are limited exceptions for exceeding the 180-day absence limit, such as:\n- Serious illness or medical treatment.\n- Compelling or compassionate reasons (e.g., a family emergency).\n\nIn such cases, you must provide evidence to support your reasons for the extended absence.\n\n### **Summary:**\nTo maintain your dependent visa and eligibility for ILR, do not stay outside the UK for more than **180 days in any 12-month period**. Always keep track of your travel history and ensure your visa conditions are met. If you have specific circumstances, consult an immigration advisor for guidance.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
